{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476554"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:49:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:49:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13803"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13803"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.46,0.29,0.04,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6420"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94999"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6420"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13803"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77973"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"645"},{"type":"tags","id":"1142"},{"type":"tags","id":"2147"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12652"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12653"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32619"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38087"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/94999"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent with a six-month history of recurrent chest infections. He has no other symptoms, has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date. On examination, he appears well. His respiratory rate is 24/min, pulse rate 100/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Chest auscultation reveals occasional wheeze. A chest X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Heimlich manoeuvre","Bronchoscopy","Rigid endoscopy","Barium swallow","Observation and reassurance"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step in management for this child is \u003Cstrong\u003Erigid endoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E. The chest X-ray has revealed a foreign body (likely a coin) in the upper oesophagus, which explains the child\u0027s recurrent respiratory symptoms. Rigid endoscopy is the preferred method for removing foreign bodies from the upper oesophagus in children, as it allows for direct visualization and controlled extraction of the object.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOesophageal foreign bodies can cause recurrent respiratory infections through several mechanisms. They can compress the trachea, leading to partial airway obstruction and impaired clearance of secretions. Additionally, they can irritate the oesophagus, causing inflammation that may spread to adjacent structures, including the trachea and lungs. This chronic irritation and inflammation can predispose the child to recurrent respiratory infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeimlich manoeuvre\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate in this case as the foreign body is not causing acute airway obstruction and has likely been present for months. Moreover, it could potentially cause the object to move and create complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E would be more appropriate if the foreign body were in the airway rather than the oesophagus. In this case, the X-ray shows the object in the oesophagus, making bronchoscopy unnecessary. If this foreign body was lodged in his upper airway, the child would have more pronounced and constant symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ebarium swallow\u003C/strong\u003E is not needed as the foreign body has already been identified on the chest X-ray. Furthermore, using contrast could complicate the subsequent removal procedure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation and reassurance\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate given the presence of a foreign body in the oesophagus. This requires prompt removal to prevent further complications such as oesophageal erosion or perforation, as well as to alleviate the recurrent respiratory symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Foreign body ingestion should be considered in children with recurrent respiratory symptoms.","Chest X-ray is an important diagnostic tool for identifying radiopaque foreign bodies in the oesophagus.","Rigid endoscopy is the preferred method for removing foreign bodies from the upper oesophagus in children.","Oesophageal foreign bodies can cause recurrent respiratory infections due to compression or irritation of the trachea."],"references":["The Royal Children\u2019s Hospital Melbourne. Foreign body ingestion. Clinical Practice Guidelines. 2023. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Foreign_body_ingestion/","Chhabra GS, Grover AS, Kaur G. Chronic retained esophageal foreign body: a case report. Int J Contemp Pediatr. 2021;8(2):383-385. Available at: https://www.ijpediatrics.com/index.php/ijcp/article/view/3962"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77973"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13803"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20746"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20746","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20746"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/O28iST9fmQdiSulBvQ4q1ofWPCEjMu.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/O28iST9fmQdiSulBvQ4q1ofWPCEjMu.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":276,"height":420}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77973","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77973"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-26T20:37:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-26T20:38:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6420"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94999"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroup